The story which Gascoigne tells is perhaps a little coloured, at least as regards the unanimous and persistent appeal ol the clergy. lt points of course to the existence of a married clergy in South Wales, and to the fact that the marriage of priests was very common in the prin· cipality. This, I believe, is well known. It is probable that there might have been some ascetic movemcnt in Dela Bere‘s diocese which brought about a numerous deputation to the bishop, and that many among the clergy may have wished, on religious grounds, to reform their practices; some, as their prayer seems to nint. from avarice, and irorn a desire to repudiate their bargain. The mention ol the sear selt for the friends of the women clearly implies that the connexion was re· cognizcd. But I see no reason to doubt that the recorded answer of the bishop is substantially accurate.
